### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

## Description

Hey!

I noticed that `[style.prop]` bindings don't give any feedback when you accidentally pass an invalid value like an object or a boolean. The browser just silently ignores the resulting CSS, which can be pretty confusing to debug.

The underlying issue (as far as I can tell) is that `SafeValue` — and its aliases like `SafeStyle` — isn't branded with a unique symbol or anything that makes it structurally distinct. At the type level it's basically `{}`, so typescript can't tell apart a real `SafeStyle` from any random object. That means the template type-checker has no way to reject invalid values at compile time.

### Examples

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `<div [style.color]="color"></div>`,
})
export class MyComponent {
  // renders style="color: [object Object]" — silently ignored
  color: any = { r: 255, g: 0, b: 0 }; 
}
```

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `<div [style.display]="isVisible"></div>`,
})
export class MyComponent {
  // renders style="display: true" — silently ignored
  isVisible = true; 
}
```

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `<img [ngSrc]="src" width="300" height="200" />`,
})
export class MyComponent {
  // ngSrc accepts string | SafeValue — but since SafeValue ≈ {},
  // the compiler can't reject this. Results in a runtime exception (NG02952).
  src = { url: 'hero.png' }; 
}
```
https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-se7avy7f

The only values that actually work at runtime are `string`, `number`, `SafeValue`, `null`, or `undefined`. Everything else just gets into garbage CSS.

For reference, this is the runtime instruction's declared signature:

```typescript
// packages/core/src/render3/instructions/styling.ts
export function ɵɵstyleProp(
  prop: string,
  value: string | number | SafeValue | undefined | null,
  suffix?: string | null,
): typeof ɵɵstyleProp
```

## Ideal solution would be branding `SafeValue`

I think the "right" fix would be to brand `SafeValue` with a unique symbol so the type-checker can actually distinguish it from `{}`. But I imagine that's a pretty significant breaking change for anyone mocking or structurally typing `SafeValue` today, so it probably deserves its own discussion.

## Proposal: dev-mode runtime warning

In the meantime, would it make sense to add a dev-mode warning when `[style.prop]` receives something that isn't `string | number | SafeValue | null | undefined`?

This feels similar in spirit to what `NgOptimizedImage` does — since `[ngSrc]` accepts `string | SafeValue` and `SafeValue ≈ {}`, you can bind any object to it without a compiler error. The directive resorts to a runtime exception because the type system can't catch the mistake. The `[style.X]` case is analogous: the types can't help here, so a runtime diagnostic seems like the right approach. The difference is that a warning (rather than a hard error) feels more appropriate since the binding still technically "works" — it just produces nonsensical CSS.

Concretely:
- Gated behind `ngDevMode` — zero cost in production.
- Non-breaking: the binding proceeds normally after the warning.
- Message includes the property name and what was received.

Something like:

```typescript
/**
 * Warns when a value bound to a style property via `[style.prop]` has an invalid type.
 * Only runs in dev mode.
 *
 * @param prop The CSS property name.
 * @param value The bound value.
 */
function warnInvalidStyleValue(prop: string, value: any): void {
  if (value == null) {
    // null/undefined are valid (they remove the style).
    return;
  }
  const type = typeof value;
  if (type === 'string' || type === 'number') {
    return;
  }
  // SafeStyle objects (from DomSanitizer.bypassSecurityTrustStyle) are valid.
  if (type === 'object' && getSanitizationBypassType(value) !== null) {
    return;
  }
  const message = formatRuntimeError(
    RuntimeErrorCode.INVALID_STYLE_PROP_VALUE,
    `\`[style.${prop}]\` was bound to a value with an invalid type. ` +
      `Expected a string, number, SafeStyle, null, or undefined, but received \`${type}\` ` +
      `(\`${stringify(value)}\`).`,
  );
  console.warn(message);
}
```

### Is this a regression?

- [x] Yes, this behavior used to work in the previous version

### The previous version in which this bug was not present was

17.3.5 (previews became native popovers in 17.3.6/17.3.7)

### Description

Since v17.3.7 the drag preview is rendered as a native popover — `preview.setAttribute('popover', 'manual')` + `showPopover()` — which is great for stacking, but it also opts the preview into the spec-mandated UA popover styles.

Per the [WHATWG HTML rendering section](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/rendering.html#flow-content-3), every `[popover]` element gets:

```css
[popover] {
  position: fixed;
  inset: 0;
  width: fit-content;
  height: fit-content;
  margin: auto;
  border: solid;
  padding: 0.25em;
  overflow: auto;      /* 👈 */
  color: CanvasText;
  background-color: Canvas;
}
```

CDK already neutralizes most of that block in [`src/cdk/drag-drop/resets.scss`](https://github.com/angular/components/blob/main/src/cdk/drag-drop/resets.scss):

```scss
@layer cdk-resets {
  .cdk-drag-preview {
    background: none;
    border: none;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;

    // Chrome sets a user agent style of `inset: 0` which combined
    // with `align-self` can break the positioning (see #29809).
    inset: auto;
  }
}
```

…but `overflow` was never included, so **every drag preview is silently a scroll container** (`getComputedStyle(preview).overflow === 'auto'`).

That stays invisible only while the preview's content happens to fit its box exactly. CDK sizes the default preview with inline `width`/`height` measured from the original element (`matchElementSize`), so any app styling on `.cdk-drag-preview` that changes the box — a 1px border, some padding — combined with the near-universal `* { box-sizing: border-box }` reset shrinks the content box below the measured content.

The result is 1–2px of scrollable overflow, and a scrollbar renders on the floating "photo" of the dragged element and rides along with the pointer. The scroll container exists in every engine that I tested (Firefox ships the identical UA rule, citing the same spec anchor); Chromium's scrollbar presentation just makes it the most visible.

<img width="1367" height="786" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/aba8c72d-47ee-43ee-9799-78ee46427478" />

---

**Related issues**:

- #29419 reported this exact symptom in the official docs sorting example (Chrome/Edge 126, July 2024). It was triaged as a docs bug and closed by #29450, which suppressed the preview's border by adding `border: none` to the example's CSS — the underlying UA style is still un-reset, so any app that styles its own preview the same way still hits it.
- #29809 is the direct precedent: another property from this same UA popover block (`inset: 0`) leaking through, fixed by extending this same reset with `inset: auto`.
- #28974 / #28976 created the `cdk-resets` layer to neutralize UA popover `color`/`background`/`border`/`padding`.
- In-repo precedent: the overlay's popover reset already handles this exact property — `.cdk-overlay-popover { … overflow: visible; … }` in [`src/cdk/overlay/_index.scss`](https://github.com/angular/components/blob/main/src/cdk/overlay/_index.scss).

Following the #29809 pattern, it looks like the reset could be completed with an explicit `overflow` declaration in the same `resets.scss` block (e.g. `overflow: clip`).

**Workaround**:

For anyone hitting this today — simply complete the reset app-side:

```css
.cdk-drag-preview {
  overflow: clip;
}
```

### Reproduction

StackBlitz link: https://stackblitz.com/edit/components-issue-starter-wr9aehf8?file=src%2Fglobal_styles.css

Steps to reproduce:

1. Open the StackBlitz preview in a Chromium browser (Chrome/Edge) and drag any row, holding it mid-drag.
2. Look at the right edge of the floating preview: a vertical scrollbar is rendered. The console also logs the preview's computed overflow (`auto auto`) and its overflow geometry (`scrollHeight > clientHeight`) mid-drag.

The repro is the docs sorting example plus two commonplace styles: a global `* { box-sizing: border-box }` reset and a 1px border on `.cdk-drag-preview` — the same effective styling the docs example produced on its preview when #29419 was filed.

Even with no author styling at all, the preview is still a scroll container (`getComputedStyle` reports `overflow: auto`); the border merely gives the overflow a visible 1–2px to show.

### Expected Behavior

The drag preview should paint exactly like the dragged element (plus any intentional `.cdk-drag-preview` styling) and should never be a scroll container. The UA popover styles should be fully neutralized by `@layer cdk-resets` the way `background`, `border`, `padding`, `color`, and `inset` already are — so an author border or padding on the preview can never produce scrollbars mid-drag.

### Actual Behavior

`getComputedStyle(document.querySelector('.cdk-drag-preview')).overflow` reports `auto` mid-drag — the UA popover style survives the reset. With a 1px preview border under `box-sizing: border-box`, measured while dragging the second row of the repro: `scrollHeight 48` vs `clientHeight 47`, with the rendered scrollbar consuming a 15px gutter (`offsetWidth 418` vs `clientWidth 401` + 2px of borders).

<img width="1364" height="774" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2400d9f0-3478-4371-a680-e8251458a3d5" />

### Environment

- Angular: 22.0.7
- CDK/Material: 22.0.5 (still reproducible against `main` — `resets.scss` has no `overflow` reset)
- Browser(s): Chrome 150 (any Chromium; Firefox has the same UA rule but paints no classic scrollbar)
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): macOS
